<DOC><DOCNO> ZF32-063-065 </DOCNO><DOCID>11 309 219</DOCID><JOURNAL>Electronic Engineering Times  Sept 9 1991 n658 p21(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Going to the movies. (Yakitori)(the future of wide-screentelevision) (column)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Lammers, David.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Wide-format 16:9 ratio televisions may see a considerable consumerinterest by the mid-1990s.andP;  Some analysts feel that it may needmore than one or two wide-format broadcasting channels showingmovies to change consumer habits and entice buyers to purchase thetelevision sets, which currently retail for around $3,500.andO;Toshiba estimates that around one million wide-format televisionswill be sold in 1995.andP;  Of that number, about 70,000 of those willbe Hi-Vision high definition television (HDTV) sets, and the restwill consist of the rival EDTV technology.andP;  For broadcastingcompanies to consider the wide-screen format, they will have tohave a substantial number of regular-format viewers tune-in to thechannel too.andP;  Proponents of the plan point to the rapidly fallingcost of large-screened televisions as the sign that many viewerswould support such a broadcasting strategy.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Future of ComputingHigh-Definition TelevisionBroadcastingTelevision SetsStandardizationIndustry Analysis.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>